WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.880
Welcome to the Data Science Hangout.

00:00:08.880 --> 00:00:14.040
If you're joining for the first time, I'm Rachel and it's great to meet you.

00:00:14.040 --> 00:00:18.879
If this is your first hangout, this is an open space for the whole data science community

00:00:18.879 --> 00:00:24.700
to connect and chat about data science leadership, questions you're facing and what's going on

00:00:24.700 --> 00:00:27.120
in the world of data science.

00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:30.459
You all have probably heard me say that a lot of times now.

00:00:30.459 --> 00:00:36.139
These sessions are recorded and shared to YouTube as well.

00:00:36.139 --> 00:00:40.380
Also on the Data Science Hangout site, so you can always go back and rewatch or find

00:00:40.380 --> 00:00:43.580
helpful resources shared there too.

00:00:43.580 --> 00:00:49.580
We always want to create spaces where everybody can participate and we can hear from everyone.

00:00:49.580 --> 00:00:53.820
So there's three ways that you can ask questions today and jump in.

00:00:53.880 --> 00:00:57.720
You can raise your hand on the Zoom chat, so I can call on you.

00:00:57.720 --> 00:01:03.320
You can put questions in the Zoom chat and feel free to just put a little star next to

00:01:03.320 --> 00:01:08.599
your question if you want me to read it out loud instead, but we also have a Slido link

00:01:08.599 --> 00:01:13.480
that Tyler or Hannah will share in just a moment in the chat, so you can ask questions

00:01:13.480 --> 00:01:16.680
anonymous or both of you at the same time.

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:22.000
You can ask questions anonymously too if you don't want to be part of the recording, but

00:01:22.099 --> 00:01:26.419
just love to reiterate, we really want to hear from everyone, no matter your level of

00:01:26.419 --> 00:01:30.820
experience or the area of work too.

00:01:30.820 --> 00:01:37.699
But with all of that, I'm so excited to be joined by my co-host for today, Alice Walsh.

00:01:37.699 --> 00:01:42.339
Alice is VP of Translational Research at Pathos.

00:01:42.339 --> 00:01:47.459
And Alice, I'd love to just have you maybe introduce yourself and a little bit about

00:01:47.459 --> 00:01:49.820
the work that you do to get us going.

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:51.360
Yeah, absolutely.

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:54.040
And let me know if you have any problems hearing me.

00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:58.959
I had a yogurt-related microphone incident before this started, so I'm hoping that everything

00:01:58.959 --> 00:01:59.959
is going to be good.

00:01:59.959 --> 00:02:02.760
Yeah, so thank you so much, Rachel, for having me.

00:02:02.760 --> 00:02:04.120
As mentioned, I'm Alice.

00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:09.279
I live here outside of Philadelphia, where I work in drug development, and I think there's

00:02:09.279 --> 00:02:14.160
probably been, I don't know, I'd be curious to hear on this call how many people do pharma

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:22.580
or research-related activities, because it's an interesting area, because pharma development

00:02:22.580 --> 00:02:24.779
has always been very data-rich, right?

00:02:24.779 --> 00:02:29.800
There's always been biostats teams who are involved in analyzing clinical trials and

00:02:29.800 --> 00:02:31.220
all that sort of stuff.

00:02:31.220 --> 00:02:35.740
And what I do is I'm involved much earlier in the process, so I've worked with everything

00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:41.080
from drug discovery teams who do target identification, like what should we even make a drug for,

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:45.259
all the way through to drugs that are in registrational trials, like big phase three

00:02:45.259 --> 00:02:50.580
studies, and we're trying to understand more around what are the patients that are responding

00:02:50.580 --> 00:02:55.020
to drugs and benefiting from drugs versus those patients who aren't.

00:02:55.020 --> 00:02:59.339
So I would describe myself as training in computational biology.

00:02:59.339 --> 00:03:04.220
So I have a couple degrees in engineering, bioengineering, biological engineering, and

00:03:04.220 --> 00:03:09.380
I got into drug development because I was really interested in working in patient data.

00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:14.440
So I did a PhD where we did some really interesting projects where at University of Pennsylvania,

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:18.759
you could work with like a neurosurgeon and get access to like brain cancer samples.

00:03:18.759 --> 00:03:22.000
And I thought like, oh, wow, this is so amazing, I can look at like 20 patients.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:24.960
And then I interviewed with people in the pharmaceutical industry, and they were like,

00:03:24.960 --> 00:03:25.960
oh, we have like 1000 patients.

00:03:25.960 --> 00:03:26.960
I was like, oh, my God, that's amazing.

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:27.960
I want to do that.

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:28.960
I want to work with patient data.

00:03:28.960 --> 00:03:36.199
And I want to try to understand, you know, what does disease mean at a molecular level?

00:03:36.199 --> 00:03:40.580
And how could we use that information to make smarter drugs, or to identify the patients

00:03:40.580 --> 00:03:42.740
that really should take our drugs.

00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:47.580
So I can say a little bit about where I've worked and things I've worked at Janssen,

00:03:47.580 --> 00:03:49.580
I worked at Bristol Myers Squibb.

00:03:49.580 --> 00:03:53.779
So those are two of like the largest pharmaceutical companies, where I was doing like biomarker

00:03:53.779 --> 00:03:58.419
type work leading teams who are working on those different aspects of drug development.

00:03:58.419 --> 00:04:01.419
And so then most recently, now I work at a startup company.

00:04:01.419 --> 00:04:04.940
So it's like the complete opposite of working at a giant company where you have lots of

00:04:05.160 --> 00:04:08.160
infrastructure and IT and things like that.

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:14.160
So I moved over to oncology therapeutic startup where I was employee number two.

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:17.160
And so now we have like five people, we're going to 10 people.

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:22.160
So it's really exciting to be part of a company where we're starting from scratch.

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:23.160
Awesome.

00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:28.160
What's been the biggest change in moving from a big company to this startup?

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:31.160
Other than the infrastructure and all that?

00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:33.160
I have a lot fewer meetings.

00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:34.160
I don't know.

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:38.880
I talked to people before about like, oh, what's it like day to day in a big company?

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:44.880
And I'm like, well, if you like having 13 meetings a day, it's fantastic.

00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:45.880
Which I'm a people person.

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:46.880
I like talking to people.

00:04:46.880 --> 00:04:51.380
So I actually didn't really mind having like nine to five, here's a meeting here, here's

00:04:51.380 --> 00:04:52.380
a meeting there.

00:04:52.380 --> 00:04:54.380
It's like a very dynamic environment.

00:04:54.380 --> 00:04:58.380
But it is difficult if you really need to like put your head down and do some a lot

00:04:58.380 --> 00:05:00.380
of like critical thinking.

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:04.600
And so I was doing all my thinking time in my car, you know, like driving between the

00:05:04.600 --> 00:05:05.600
office and the house.

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:10.600
And now I work from home and I don't have that time, but I just have a lot more non

00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:16.600
meeting time to like do some thinking, strategizing, come up with crazy ideas, all that sort of

00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:17.600
stuff.

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:21.600
So that's the biggest difference, fewer meetings, because when there's only four people at a

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:24.600
company, it's really hard to talk to them all day.

00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:29.600
By definition, the math doesn't work to have like 13 meetings a day.

00:05:29.820 --> 00:05:30.820
Definitely.

00:05:30.820 --> 00:05:33.820
I wasn't actually going to wait to ask this question of it, because you just said a lot

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:36.820
of your thinking happened in driving to work.

00:05:36.820 --> 00:05:39.820
And I switched to remote work.

00:05:39.820 --> 00:05:44.820
I know something you are interested in is optimizing remote work and remote teams.

00:05:44.820 --> 00:05:49.820
So curious to just hear a bit about your thoughts on that.

00:05:49.820 --> 00:05:50.820
Yeah.

00:05:50.820 --> 00:05:51.820
Or what you're facing.

00:05:51.820 --> 00:05:53.820
Yeah, no, I was thinking about that a lot.

00:05:53.820 --> 00:05:55.820
Like this weekend, I went for a bike ride.

00:05:56.040 --> 00:06:00.040
And I was having all these like ideas when I probably should have been like paying attention

00:06:00.040 --> 00:06:02.040
to not getting hit by a car or something.

00:06:02.040 --> 00:06:08.040
But yeah, now I have like all the good ideas come like on the treadmill, on the bike, in

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:09.040
the shower.

00:06:09.040 --> 00:06:12.040
Like, I don't have the car time.

00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:16.040
And I guess also I probably should have been doing like a lot of thinking in the car when

00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:18.040
I was supposed to be paying attention to the road.

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:25.040
But yeah, I would love to talk to people about how they're doing remote work well, especially

00:06:25.260 --> 00:06:27.260
for data teams, right?

00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:34.260
Like, if I think about the types of interactions that I'm having, like, you don't necessarily

00:06:34.260 --> 00:06:39.260
want to like make a big slide deck to explain something to a colleague or a coworker.

00:06:39.260 --> 00:06:44.260
So like communicating effectively when all you have is like Slack huddles and like Zoom

00:06:44.260 --> 00:06:48.260
meetings and all those sorts of things is a challenge.

00:06:48.260 --> 00:06:53.260
Before I joined this startup, I was remote working as well to some extent, right?

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:59.480
So thanks to the pandemic, but even without the pandemic, I was on a team where I had

00:06:59.480 --> 00:07:04.480
direct reports in Boston, New Jersey, and San Francisco.

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:08.480
So we were already like a distributed team and we were working with people in Spain.

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:14.480
So we were working across like a, I don't know how many hours time zone, which is like

00:07:14.480 --> 00:07:15.480
an interesting challenge.

00:07:15.480 --> 00:07:20.480
But I would love to hear how other people are optimizing for that because I just feel

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:22.480
like there's got to be a better way.

00:07:22.700 --> 00:07:27.700
Like people have got to learn something in the last two years of pandemic about how to

00:07:27.700 --> 00:07:29.700
do remote work really, really well.

00:07:30.700 --> 00:07:34.700
Yeah, I'd love to open it up to everyone if you have thoughts or want to share anything

00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:36.700
in the chat too.

00:07:41.700 --> 00:07:48.700
I can share about what I just posted, which is about the book Rest by Alex Ping.

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:52.920
So Rest is, if you haven't read it, you should totally go read it.

00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:53.920
It's fantastic.

00:07:53.920 --> 00:07:57.920
It gives lots of different accounts of different people.

00:07:57.920 --> 00:07:59.920
Lots of them are scientists.

00:07:59.920 --> 00:08:01.920
Some of them are technology people.

00:08:02.920 --> 00:08:07.920
And it's accounts kind of all throughout history of famous scientists who use their

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:12.920
downtime to do their background brain work, right?

00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:19.140
Like the walking around on campus or the mountain climbing or the whatever that they

00:08:19.140 --> 00:08:24.140
did was really essential to the background brain processes that they needed to have ideas

00:08:24.140 --> 00:08:26.140
and think and all of that stuff.

00:08:27.140 --> 00:08:32.140
I've been working remotely since 2015 and I feel like I was not very good at it for

00:08:32.140 --> 00:08:33.140
a long time.

00:08:33.140 --> 00:08:39.140
But I had a director at one point who was like, I need you to like take 15 minute walks

00:08:39.140 --> 00:08:40.140
during your day.

00:08:40.140 --> 00:08:41.140
It's like bill them as hours.

00:08:41.140 --> 00:08:42.140
They're billable hours.

00:08:42.359 --> 00:08:44.359
This is part of you working for this client.

00:08:44.359 --> 00:08:45.359
I need you to go take walks.

00:08:46.359 --> 00:08:49.359
And that really helped like building that into your schedule so that you have the white

00:08:49.359 --> 00:08:53.359
space to let your brain do background work is really important.

00:08:53.359 --> 00:08:57.359
Otherwise, you just sit there and you're at your screen for longer than a couple of

00:08:57.359 --> 00:09:01.359
hours and your brain stops doing all that background process work because you're

00:09:01.359 --> 00:09:05.359
forcing it to do too much stuff that's in front of your face.

00:09:07.359 --> 00:09:08.359
I love that.

00:09:09.359 --> 00:09:10.359
Really good recommendation.

00:09:10.359 --> 00:09:11.359
I'm going to check out this book.

00:09:12.359 --> 00:09:17.359
I see Ravonda, you also put some thoughts into the chat, too, if you want to jump in.

00:09:23.359 --> 00:09:24.359
Sure.

00:09:24.359 --> 00:09:33.359
I would like to get any advice on how we can work to make brainstorming work better virtually

00:09:33.359 --> 00:09:39.359
because it seems like that is an area where people are so excited to get out of meetings

00:09:39.359 --> 00:09:40.359
when they're virtual.

00:09:40.580 --> 00:09:44.580
If anyone has any ideas about how to improve on that process, that would be great.

00:09:46.580 --> 00:09:47.580
I can say a couple things.

00:09:49.580 --> 00:09:50.580
Sorry, I just saw in the chat, too.

00:09:50.580 --> 00:09:51.580
Someone said get a dog.

00:09:51.580 --> 00:09:52.580
Don't get a dog.

00:09:52.580 --> 00:09:56.580
I'm just looking at my dog whining at me from like outside in the other room.

00:09:56.580 --> 00:09:57.580
They're not good.

00:09:58.580 --> 00:10:01.580
The yeah, the brainstorming thing is the one that I've been trying out a couple of

00:10:01.580 --> 00:10:06.580
things like there are online platforms like Mural and probably like I've used a couple

00:10:06.799 --> 00:10:09.799
other ones where you can like drag around stickies and you can like everybody can kind

00:10:09.799 --> 00:10:12.799
of collaborate on like this big whiteboard together.

00:10:13.799 --> 00:10:17.799
I found that those can be like difficult to use, but some of the concepts are useful.

00:10:17.799 --> 00:10:23.799
So like in my team, we've done brainstorming or we just use Google Slides and basically

00:10:23.799 --> 00:10:28.799
like to prepare for the brainstorming, I do some prep work around like here are the like

00:10:28.799 --> 00:10:33.799
high level like what if questions that we're trying to get ideas around and then like have

00:10:34.020 --> 00:10:38.020
people go off and do their own brainstorming on separate slides.

00:10:38.020 --> 00:10:41.020
So like it's really low tech like I'll be like, here's your slide.

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:42.020
Here's your slide.

00:10:42.020 --> 00:10:46.020
Here's your slide and everybody write down like as many ideas as they can and it's

00:10:46.020 --> 00:10:51.020
like the no bad ideas kind of concept and then after like 10 or 15 minutes of everybody

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:53.020
doing individually and not looking at each other's ideas.

00:10:53.020 --> 00:10:57.020
Then we come back together and we try to move them around like categorize them.

00:10:57.020 --> 00:11:01.020
So like we say like, okay, it looks like there's actually like five ideas here.

00:11:01.239 --> 00:11:05.239
And so let's start a new slide for each of those ideas and everybody can like move

00:11:05.239 --> 00:11:06.239
their ideas around.

00:11:06.239 --> 00:11:10.239
So you can see how some tools where you can like really like drag and drop stuff would

00:11:10.239 --> 00:11:11.239
be great.

00:11:11.239 --> 00:11:14.239
But Google Slides is a very low tech way to get the same effect.

00:11:14.239 --> 00:11:19.239
And then you can start to build on people's ideas like okay, great idea to do this.

00:11:19.239 --> 00:11:22.239
But what if we also did this other thing and pulled it together?

00:11:22.239 --> 00:11:26.239
So I've actually been really excited about the brainstorming that I can do online.

00:11:26.460 --> 00:11:31.460
I think that's actually maybe one of the places where like everybody calling in is

00:11:31.460 --> 00:11:33.460
kind of like a great equalizer.

00:11:33.460 --> 00:11:37.460
Because I know I have colleagues and things who aren't going to like stand up and say

00:11:37.460 --> 00:11:40.460
like, let me take over the whiteboard and tell you all my great ideas.

00:11:40.460 --> 00:11:42.460
They might sit back in a meeting.

00:11:42.460 --> 00:11:46.460
But when you give everybody their own slide, people are really happy to like quietly like

00:11:46.460 --> 00:11:48.460
fill out their own ideas and put things there.

00:11:48.460 --> 00:11:51.460
It kind of like levels the playing field.

00:11:51.460 --> 00:11:55.460
I like that especially the part about giving everyone their own slide because I've noticed

00:11:55.679 --> 00:11:59.679
in some meetings, people who are a little bit more introverted may feel a little bit

00:11:59.679 --> 00:12:02.679
more shy at online meetings, at least in my experience.

00:12:02.679 --> 00:12:05.679
So I like the idea that everyone has at least a small space.

00:12:05.679 --> 00:12:09.679
And I like the idea of brainstorming separately and kind of coming together collectively.

00:12:09.679 --> 00:12:10.679
I like that a lot.

00:12:10.679 --> 00:12:11.679
Thank you.

00:12:11.679 --> 00:12:12.679
Yeah.

00:12:12.679 --> 00:12:14.679
And then you have the document too as a record, right?

00:12:14.679 --> 00:12:15.679
It's shared with everybody.

00:12:15.679 --> 00:12:19.679
And you can like, I don't know, I guess I'm trying to think if there's other platforms

00:12:19.679 --> 00:12:20.679
that this works well for.

00:12:20.679 --> 00:12:24.679
I'm just realizing that like my previous job where we used like Microsoft, I don't know

00:12:24.900 --> 00:12:28.900
how, I can't remember if you can like actively all edit the same PowerPoint.

00:12:28.900 --> 00:12:29.900
I think so.

00:12:29.900 --> 00:12:30.900
It's the same idea.

00:12:30.900 --> 00:12:31.900
But yeah.

00:12:31.900 --> 00:12:40.900
I see Mark, you suggested Zoom's whiteboard feature too, if you want to share that or

00:12:40.900 --> 00:12:41.900
how that works.

00:12:41.900 --> 00:12:44.900
I don't know why I've never tried that out before.

00:12:44.900 --> 00:12:46.900
We should try it out now.

00:12:46.900 --> 00:12:47.900
It is pretty nifty.

00:12:47.900 --> 00:12:49.900
You can just write on like the screen.

00:12:49.900 --> 00:12:52.900
So if you need like a true, well, hang on.

00:12:53.119 --> 00:12:56.119
It's been actually a while since I've used it.

00:12:56.119 --> 00:13:01.119
I can't recall if you can just write directly on the screen or if there is like a true whiteboard

00:13:01.119 --> 00:13:02.119
whiteboard.

00:13:02.119 --> 00:13:04.119
I think it gives you the option of either.

00:13:04.119 --> 00:13:07.119
But I've used it sparingly since I've started.

00:13:07.119 --> 00:13:10.119
My team has started coming back into the office more often.

00:13:10.119 --> 00:13:16.119
But I've found that that's been helpful when we were like walking through some technical

00:13:16.119 --> 00:13:20.119
topics that like needed like a quick, just like hand sketch.

00:13:20.340 --> 00:13:26.340
It's kind of wonky to do it with a mouse, but it's better than trying to describe something

00:13:26.340 --> 00:13:28.340
visual to someone.

00:13:29.340 --> 00:13:30.340
Cool.

00:13:30.340 --> 00:13:33.340
I love this topic of brainstorming too.

00:13:33.340 --> 00:13:38.340
George, I see you put some thoughts in the chat too, if you want to jump in.

00:13:41.340 --> 00:13:42.340
Hey.

00:13:42.340 --> 00:13:43.340
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:13:43.340 --> 00:13:46.340
No, I was just saying on top of the walking.

00:13:46.559 --> 00:13:51.559
I know Elizabeth mentioned billable walks, which I think I think is great.

00:13:51.559 --> 00:13:56.559
And I've worked at consultancy where you would definitely encourage to to include thinking

00:13:56.559 --> 00:13:58.559
time, which was which was great.

00:13:58.559 --> 00:14:01.559
But it doesn't it doesn't have to be a walk.

00:14:01.559 --> 00:14:04.559
It just is anything where you get rid of your screens for a minute.

00:14:04.559 --> 00:14:09.559
So I I'm like, I always have notepads in front of me.

00:14:09.559 --> 00:14:11.559
So I'm like writing most of my ideas.

00:14:11.780 --> 00:14:15.780
And then I end up because we do a lot of work on Slack.

00:14:15.780 --> 00:14:19.780
Half of my messages are just a photo of a whiteboard or a photo of a sheet where I'm

00:14:19.780 --> 00:14:23.780
like, I've written all this stuff down and I want to put it in a document, but I can't

00:14:23.780 --> 00:14:24.780
I don't have time or whatever.

00:14:24.780 --> 00:14:28.780
So I just send it to someone else and they end up having to deal with messy content.

00:14:28.780 --> 00:14:30.780
So I'm probably a nightmare to work with.

00:14:30.780 --> 00:14:33.780
But I definitely encourage getting away from screens.

00:14:33.780 --> 00:14:38.780
And the physical act of writing is shown to be really helpful for memory and that sort

00:14:38.780 --> 00:14:39.780
of thing.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
It's why you write notes when you're in lectures and that sort of thing.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
It's not for the content.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:48.000
I don't think as much as it is for you to get that connection with what you're doing.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:49.000
So, yeah.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:51.000
Yeah, definitely.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:56.000
And then you're focusing on one thing instead of a million things on your screen at once.

