00:21:35.300 --> 00:21:39.300
I work for a company where we're all primarily epidemiologists or come

00:21:39.300 --> 00:21:41.300
from some kind of a research background.

00:21:41.300 --> 00:21:43.300
And I work in med tech.

00:21:43.300 --> 00:21:47.300
But basically we were a team that was primarily SAS users.

00:21:47.300 --> 00:21:49.300
And then we switched over to R.

00:21:49.300 --> 00:21:53.300
And it was a real, like it was definitely a challenge.

00:21:53.300 --> 00:21:57.300
We made the change because of financial reasons pretty much.

00:21:57.300 --> 00:21:59.300
Yeah.

00:21:59.300 --> 00:22:02.300
Honestly, I think people are really happy we made the switch.

00:22:02.520 --> 00:22:06.520
I think what helped a lot was the R for Data Science book.

00:22:06.520 --> 00:22:08.520
So I really recommend people read that.

00:22:08.520 --> 00:22:12.520
And I think when a lot of people who use SAS are coming from this

00:22:12.520 --> 00:22:16.520
research background and a lot of data science, I think, is really

00:22:16.520 --> 00:22:20.520
structured in this more computer science framework.

00:22:20.520 --> 00:22:24.520
And so focusing on the tidyverse and going through R for Data Science

00:22:24.520 --> 00:22:28.520
and really breaking things down into kind of step-by-step research

00:22:28.739 --> 00:22:32.739
really helped my team get acclimated to R.

00:22:32.739 --> 00:22:34.739
So that's what we did.

00:22:34.739 --> 00:22:38.739
We really broke it down by each step of the analytic process.

00:22:38.739 --> 00:22:42.739
And we kind of went along with the R for Data Science book.

00:22:42.739 --> 00:22:46.739
And we just looked at, okay, how do we import our data?

00:22:46.739 --> 00:22:50.739
How do we, you know, get some basic frequencies?

00:22:50.739 --> 00:22:54.739
I tried to like, as I was learning it, I tried to compare it like

00:22:54.959 --> 00:22:58.959
the count function in the tidyverse to using PROC FREQ and SAS.

00:22:58.959 --> 00:23:02.959
So there was a lot of like trying to compare things.

00:23:02.959 --> 00:23:06.959
And there's also a great online book out there.

00:23:06.959 --> 00:23:10.959
Sometimes there's maybe too many books for R online.

00:23:10.959 --> 00:23:14.959
But there's one called the Epidemiologist Handbook for using R.

00:23:14.959 --> 00:23:16.959
I can share a link.

00:23:16.959 --> 00:23:20.959
But I thought that was really great for kind of helping my team switch

00:23:21.180 --> 00:23:25.180
and really make those comparisons a lot.

00:23:25.180 --> 00:23:29.180
Yeah, that'd be great if you could share that link in the chat too.

