00:38:20.219 --> 00:38:22.219
just not within your company.

00:38:22.219 --> 00:38:24.219
So you have to go out, and you have to get it.

00:38:24.219 --> 00:38:26.219
I feel like that's one of the key

00:38:26.219 --> 00:38:28.219
differences, is that

00:38:28.219 --> 00:38:30.219
like, yeah,

00:38:30.219 --> 00:38:32.219
you have to do it differently that way.

00:38:32.219 --> 00:38:34.219
I think it's still all there, though.

00:38:34.219 --> 00:38:36.219
It's not like I have to become all of a sudden

00:38:36.219 --> 00:38:38.219
an expert. I'm not going to become

00:38:38.439 --> 00:38:40.439
a medicinal chemist,

00:38:40.439 --> 00:38:42.439
but I can get a contract

00:38:42.439 --> 00:38:44.439
with a medicinal chemist to consult with me.

00:38:44.439 --> 00:38:46.439
That's maybe one

00:38:46.439 --> 00:38:48.439
big difference. The other thing would be the focus.

00:38:48.439 --> 00:38:50.439
We just have a slightly

00:38:50.439 --> 00:38:52.439
smaller focus,

00:38:52.439 --> 00:38:54.439
and also

00:38:54.439 --> 00:38:56.439
the need to pivot from project

00:38:56.439 --> 00:38:58.439
to project as priorities dictate

00:38:58.439 --> 00:39:00.439
is probably a little bit smaller.

00:39:00.439 --> 00:39:02.439
Thank you.

00:39:02.439 --> 00:39:04.439
I see

00:39:04.439 --> 00:39:06.439
Jian,

00:39:06.659 --> 00:39:08.659
you had a follow-up

00:39:08.659 --> 00:39:10.659
question from the question before.

00:39:10.659 --> 00:39:12.659
Do you want to jump in?

00:39:12.659 --> 00:39:14.659
Oh, yeah.

00:39:14.659 --> 00:39:16.659
I'm sorry. Yeah, this is Jian.

00:39:16.659 --> 00:39:18.659
Awesome.

00:39:18.659 --> 00:39:20.659
We can hear you.

00:39:20.659 --> 00:39:22.659
Sorry.

00:39:22.659 --> 00:39:24.659
Yeah, so

00:39:24.659 --> 00:39:26.659
Alec, you just

00:39:26.659 --> 00:39:28.659
talked about how you

00:39:28.659 --> 00:39:30.659
treat data with record

00:39:30.659 --> 00:39:32.659
anytime that you change it,

00:39:32.659 --> 00:39:34.659
especially for those missing data.

00:39:34.879 --> 00:39:36.879
I just wonder

00:39:36.879 --> 00:39:38.879
what was your

00:39:38.879 --> 00:39:40.879
during the project

00:39:40.879 --> 00:39:42.879
what was your

00:39:42.879 --> 00:39:44.879
the

00:39:44.879 --> 00:39:46.879
frequency of changing

00:39:46.879 --> 00:39:48.879
your missing data

00:39:48.879 --> 00:39:50.879
replaced by the

00:39:50.879 --> 00:39:52.879
mean?

00:39:52.879 --> 00:39:54.879
Do you often do that or you

00:39:54.879 --> 00:39:56.879
totally not doing it by

00:39:56.879 --> 00:39:58.879
each cases?

00:39:58.879 --> 00:40:00.879
Yeah.

00:40:00.879 --> 00:40:02.879
That's a great question.

00:40:03.100 --> 00:40:05.100
I think it's always going to depend on

00:40:05.100 --> 00:40:07.100
your use case here, what you do.

00:40:07.100 --> 00:40:09.100
I've been involved

00:40:09.100 --> 00:40:11.100
in projects before where there are

00:40:11.100 --> 00:40:13.100
different methods to impute missing data.

00:40:13.100 --> 00:40:15.100
And

00:40:15.100 --> 00:40:17.100
a couple good R packages to do this as

00:40:17.100 --> 00:40:19.100
well, but I don't want to say the names off

00:40:19.100 --> 00:40:21.100
the top of my head in case I get them wrong.

00:40:21.100 --> 00:40:23.100
But yeah,

00:40:23.100 --> 00:40:25.100
sometimes you do need to impute missing

00:40:25.100 --> 00:40:27.100
data. Yeah, exactly.

00:40:27.100 --> 00:40:29.100
Mice is probably one of them.

00:40:29.100 --> 00:40:31.100
But it depends on

00:40:31.320 --> 00:40:33.320
what you're doing and whether you want to

00:40:33.320 --> 00:40:35.320
impute data or not.

00:40:35.320 --> 00:40:37.320
It depends on your

00:40:37.320 --> 00:40:39.320
use case.

00:40:39.320 --> 00:40:41.320
And then you don't have

00:40:41.320 --> 00:40:43.320
an estimated

00:40:43.320 --> 00:40:45.320
how often you do that?

00:40:45.320 --> 00:40:47.320
No.

00:40:47.320 --> 00:40:49.320
No idea. Sorry.

00:40:49.320 --> 00:40:51.320
It's not like a habit you should

00:40:51.320 --> 00:40:53.320
establish, right?

00:40:53.320 --> 00:40:55.320
Yeah, but I think it's a

00:40:55.320 --> 00:40:57.320
challenge of working with

00:40:57.320 --> 00:40:59.320
it really is sometimes

00:40:59.540 --> 00:41:01.540
you can think

00:41:01.540 --> 00:41:03.540
about different things when you're working

00:41:03.540 --> 00:41:05.540
with data, right?

00:41:05.540 --> 00:41:07.540
The answer is always it depends.

00:41:07.540 --> 00:41:09.540
But one thing to keep in mind

00:41:09.540 --> 00:41:11.540
is sometimes we tend to think

00:41:11.540 --> 00:41:13.540
the data comes

00:41:13.540 --> 00:41:15.540
from somewhere and

00:41:15.540 --> 00:41:17.540
now we have the data and we have to deal

00:41:17.540 --> 00:41:19.540
with it. And we can engineer this crazy

00:41:19.540 --> 00:41:21.540
complicated solution around the data or whatever.

00:41:21.540 --> 00:41:23.540
But the data didn't come from

00:41:23.540 --> 00:41:25.540
a fairy that came and said data.

00:41:25.540 --> 00:41:27.540
The data came from a machine or

00:41:27.760 --> 00:41:29.760
a person or a study or something like that.

00:41:29.760 --> 00:41:31.760
And that's often hard that

00:41:31.760 --> 00:41:33.760
we just don't even think about that. It's like, okay,

00:41:33.760 --> 00:41:35.760
the data came and now we have the data. Well, the data

00:41:35.760 --> 00:41:37.760
didn't come from magic. You could

00:41:37.760 --> 00:41:39.760
go and talk and see if you can get some of that data.

00:41:39.760 --> 00:41:41.760
So if it's a

00:41:41.760 --> 00:41:43.760
clinical study or something,

00:41:43.760 --> 00:41:45.760
there's a site who put in that data

00:41:45.760 --> 00:41:47.760
and you can go and talk to them and try to

00:41:47.760 --> 00:41:49.760
get different data or rerun

00:41:49.760 --> 00:41:51.760
a plate or something if there's

00:41:51.760 --> 00:41:53.760
a QC problem or

00:41:53.760 --> 00:41:55.760
something like that. And I think that's something

00:41:55.979 --> 00:41:57.979
I personally forget all the time

00:41:57.979 --> 00:41:59.979
because I'm just so used to like,

00:41:59.979 --> 00:42:01.979
I have to over-engineer a solution to my data

00:42:01.979 --> 00:42:03.979
versus trying to get better data.

00:42:03.979 --> 00:42:05.979
I see.

00:42:05.979 --> 00:42:07.979
I like all these comments in the chat too.

00:42:07.979 --> 00:42:09.979
There's some great

00:42:09.979 --> 00:42:11.979
comments in the chat about mice.

00:42:11.979 --> 00:42:13.979
And you don't

00:42:13.979 --> 00:42:15.979
really just drop it, right?

00:42:15.979 --> 00:42:17.979
You just keep it or whatever.

00:42:17.979 --> 00:42:19.979
Depends on.

00:42:19.979 --> 00:42:21.979
I'm going to go back to it. It depends.

00:42:21.979 --> 00:42:23.979
It depends on your question, right?

00:42:24.199 --> 00:42:26.199
I think that you're really

00:42:26.199 --> 00:42:28.199
biasing your population

00:42:28.199 --> 00:42:30.199
a lot by removing and only

00:42:30.199 --> 00:42:32.199
looking at the patients that have that data

00:42:32.199 --> 00:42:34.199
or don't have that data. That's the question

00:42:34.199 --> 00:42:36.199
really, right? So certainly,

00:42:36.199 --> 00:42:38.199
yeah, sometimes you

00:42:38.199 --> 00:42:40.199
only look at a subset.

00:42:40.199 --> 00:42:42.199
That's generally how biomarker studies work,

00:42:42.199 --> 00:42:44.199
right? If you have a large clinical

00:42:44.199 --> 00:42:46.199
study, you're not going to have biomarker

00:42:46.199 --> 00:42:48.199
data on all the patients. And that's because

00:42:48.199 --> 00:42:50.199
there wasn't a sample available.

00:42:50.199 --> 00:42:52.199
The sample didn't generate

00:42:52.419 --> 00:42:54.419
meaningful data. There's a lot of failure

00:42:54.419 --> 00:42:56.419
rates when you're working with biological

00:42:56.419 --> 00:42:58.419
samples. So you end up evaluating

00:42:58.419 --> 00:43:00.419
a biomarker population versus the whole

00:43:00.419 --> 00:43:02.419
population. But the key is always

00:43:02.419 --> 00:43:04.419
to demonstrate or to evaluate how

00:43:04.419 --> 00:43:06.419
similar that population is

00:43:06.419 --> 00:43:08.419
to your larger sample,

00:43:08.419 --> 00:43:10.419
which again is not really representative

00:43:10.419 --> 00:43:12.419
of all patients, but that's the idea.

00:43:12.419 --> 00:43:14.419
And it's really important because sometimes

00:43:14.419 --> 00:43:16.419
you can have a biomarker

00:43:16.419 --> 00:43:18.419
population that is skewed

00:43:18.419 --> 00:43:20.419
and somehow biased, and then it would not

00:43:20.639 --> 00:43:22.639
be a good population.

00:43:22.639 --> 00:43:24.639
Thank you so much.

00:43:24.639 --> 00:43:26.639
Thanks for the question, too.

00:43:26.639 --> 00:43:28.639
I see on the slide there's a bunch

00:43:28.639 --> 00:43:30.639
of questions coming in, too, and I love

00:43:30.639 --> 00:43:32.639
this one that just

00:43:32.639 --> 00:43:34.639
came in. What leadership qualities

00:43:34.639 --> 00:43:36.639
have made the biggest mark on you,

00:43:36.639 --> 00:43:38.639
positive and or negative?

00:43:40.639 --> 00:43:42.639
Leadership qualities?

00:43:42.639 --> 00:43:44.639
Yes. What leadership qualities

00:43:44.639 --> 00:43:46.639
have made the biggest mark on you?

00:43:46.639 --> 00:43:48.639
I mean, I tend

00:43:48.860 --> 00:43:50.860
to think

00:43:50.860 --> 00:43:52.860
of good leaders that I've had in the past

00:43:52.860 --> 00:43:54.860
and what made a good leader.

00:43:54.860 --> 00:43:56.860
And so I apologize,

00:43:56.860 --> 00:43:58.860
I've probably sworn already three times

00:43:58.860 --> 00:44:00.860
on this, so let me try to think of a way to say it

00:44:00.860 --> 00:44:02.860
without swearing.

00:44:02.860 --> 00:44:04.860
The number one thing is don't be a jerk.

00:44:04.860 --> 00:44:06.860
There are plenty of good leaders

00:44:06.860 --> 00:44:08.860
who are complete a-holes, and there are

00:44:08.860 --> 00:44:10.860
plenty of people who are successful

00:44:10.860 --> 00:44:12.860
who aren't. So there's got to be a choice

00:44:12.860 --> 00:44:14.860
there. And so I think there are

00:44:14.860 --> 00:44:16.860
great leaders who really care about

00:44:17.080 --> 00:44:19.080
the people that they work with

00:44:19.080 --> 00:44:21.080
and

00:44:21.080 --> 00:44:23.080
try to do right by people.

00:44:23.080 --> 00:44:25.080
I think we've all had managers

00:44:25.080 --> 00:44:27.080
where in the past they've made

00:44:27.080 --> 00:44:29.080
your life miserable, but I fundamentally

00:44:29.080 --> 00:44:31.080
don't believe that people wake up in the morning and are like,

00:44:31.080 --> 00:44:33.080
I'm going to come to work and do a crappy job

00:44:33.080 --> 00:44:35.080
and I'm going to make everybody unhappy.

00:44:35.080 --> 00:44:37.080
It's all these other circumstances that

00:44:37.080 --> 00:44:39.080
make somebody be toxic in a work environment,

00:44:39.080 --> 00:44:41.080
but yeah, so leadership is number one,

00:44:41.080 --> 00:44:43.080
don't be a jerk. I think the other thing

00:44:43.080 --> 00:44:45.080
is really communication.

00:44:45.300 --> 00:44:47.300
I forget if people are communicating up and down.

00:44:47.300 --> 00:44:49.300
If you're a manager,

00:44:49.300 --> 00:44:51.300
you have to communicate a lot with your reports,

00:44:51.300 --> 00:44:53.300
but you also need to communicate a lot

00:44:53.300 --> 00:44:55.300
with your management and then your peers.

00:44:55.300 --> 00:44:57.300
And especially

00:44:57.300 --> 00:44:59.300
to advocate for your team.

00:44:59.300 --> 00:45:01.300
I think the leaders that I really respect

00:45:01.300 --> 00:45:03.300
are the people who are all constantly advocating

00:45:03.300 --> 00:45:05.300
for their team.

00:45:05.300 --> 00:45:07.300
I go to a lot of conferences

00:45:07.300 --> 00:45:09.300
and things, and the people who

00:45:09.300 --> 00:45:11.300
are constantly giving credit for the people

00:45:11.300 --> 00:45:13.300
who did the work, those are the kind

00:45:13.520 --> 00:45:15.520
of, I'm like, wow, they're great.

00:45:15.520 --> 00:45:17.520
I like them. Great job.

00:45:17.520 --> 00:45:19.520
When somebody doesn't have any acknowledgments

00:45:19.520 --> 00:45:21.520
or anything in their slides, I'm like,

00:45:21.520 --> 00:45:23.520
what? What's going on?

00:45:23.520 --> 00:45:25.520
Nobody wants to work for them.

00:45:25.520 --> 00:45:27.520
Right?

00:45:27.520 --> 00:45:29.520
So, yeah, people who

00:45:29.520 --> 00:45:31.520
are generous, who communicate a lot,

00:45:31.520 --> 00:45:33.520
those are kind of the leadership qualities

00:45:33.520 --> 00:45:35.520
that I tend to hone in on, like am I doing a good enough

00:45:35.520 --> 00:45:37.520
job communicating?

00:45:37.520 --> 00:45:39.520
I think the third thing

00:45:39.520 --> 00:45:41.520
is seeing the big picture.

00:45:41.739 --> 00:45:43.739
So that's probably kind of some overlap

00:45:43.739 --> 00:45:45.739
there with the other two.

00:45:45.739 --> 00:45:47.739
Sometimes people get promoted into leadership

00:45:47.739 --> 00:45:49.739
positions because they're really good at their

00:45:49.739 --> 00:45:51.739
technical work.

00:45:51.739 --> 00:45:53.739
But I think

00:45:53.739 --> 00:45:55.739
being able to see a bigger picture

00:45:55.739 --> 00:45:57.739
of how your work fits into that larger

00:45:57.739 --> 00:45:59.739
picture is very, very important.

00:46:01.739 --> 00:46:03.739
Yeah. And you don't have to be

00:46:03.739 --> 00:46:05.739
constantly giving TED Talks and things about

00:46:05.739 --> 00:46:07.739
your vision and

00:46:07.739 --> 00:46:09.739
how you can see everything about the future.

00:46:09.959 --> 00:46:11.959
But being able to help

00:46:11.959 --> 00:46:13.959
connect what everybody's doing to

00:46:13.959 --> 00:46:15.959
the mission of the company or to

00:46:15.959 --> 00:46:17.959
some sort of bigger impact is really important

00:46:17.959 --> 00:46:19.959
because it's just very demotivating

00:46:19.959 --> 00:46:21.959
if you're working on something and you can't

00:46:21.959 --> 00:46:23.959
see how it relates to

00:46:23.959 --> 00:46:25.959
something

00:46:25.959 --> 00:46:27.959
bigger than your individual work.

00:46:29.959 --> 00:46:31.959
That's such a good point.

00:46:31.959 --> 00:46:33.959
I always seem to notice that, too, in

00:46:33.959 --> 00:46:35.959
presentations when people are highlighting

00:46:35.959 --> 00:46:37.959
others on their team.

00:46:38.179 --> 00:46:40.179
I just feel like it's such an easy win.

00:46:40.179 --> 00:46:42.179
Why not be more

00:46:42.179 --> 00:46:44.179
generous?

00:46:44.179 --> 00:46:46.179
Definitely. I see

00:46:46.179 --> 00:46:48.179
there's quite a few packages that are being

00:46:48.179 --> 00:46:50.179
shared in the chat, too.

00:46:50.179 --> 00:46:52.179
I'm going to ask this question now.

