00:48:04.840 --> 00:48:06.840
message with a question, so I'll ask

00:48:06.840 --> 00:48:08.840
it.

00:48:08.840 --> 00:48:10.840
What do you find to be

00:48:10.840 --> 00:48:12.840
the most effective way to communicate

00:48:12.840 --> 00:48:14.840
your data insights to stakeholders,

00:48:14.840 --> 00:48:16.840
especially stakeholders

00:48:16.840 --> 00:48:18.840
you might not engage with as much?

00:48:18.840 --> 00:48:20.840
This is where I can

00:48:20.840 --> 00:48:22.840
use help on remote work, right?

00:48:22.840 --> 00:48:24.840
I do think

00:48:24.840 --> 00:48:26.840
that sometimes the most effective

00:48:26.840 --> 00:48:28.840
communications I've had have been in person.

00:48:28.840 --> 00:48:30.840
I don't have that

00:48:31.060 --> 00:48:33.060
anymore, really, usually.

00:48:33.060 --> 00:48:35.060
We don't do a lot of in-person

00:48:35.060 --> 00:48:37.060
stuff.

00:48:37.060 --> 00:48:39.060
That's where I would love to hear how

00:48:39.060 --> 00:48:41.060
other people are doing things. I think there are

00:48:41.060 --> 00:48:43.060
different schools of thought. Sometimes

00:48:43.060 --> 00:48:45.060
it's like, okay, you need something interactive

00:48:45.060 --> 00:48:47.060
so somebody can explore and then make

00:48:47.060 --> 00:48:49.060
their own interpretations

00:48:49.060 --> 00:48:51.060
or whatever. I tend to not think

00:48:51.060 --> 00:48:53.060
that. I'm more of a fan of

00:48:53.060 --> 00:48:55.060
the executive summary

00:48:55.060 --> 00:48:57.060
where I'm like, here's

00:48:57.060 --> 00:48:59.060
exactly what I mean. No

00:48:59.280 --> 00:49:01.280
it's like, here's the result. I've seen

00:49:01.280 --> 00:49:03.280
a lot of people come up with slides or

00:49:03.280 --> 00:49:05.280
presentations or something where it's like,

00:49:05.280 --> 00:49:07.280
here's a bunch of things I did. I did this.

00:49:07.280 --> 00:49:09.280
Here's a plot. I did this. Here's a table. I did this.

00:49:09.280 --> 00:49:11.280
Here's a table. I prefer

00:49:11.280 --> 00:49:13.280
if somebody comes to the table

00:49:13.280 --> 00:49:15.280
or comes to the meeting or whatever and says,

00:49:15.280 --> 00:49:17.280
here's actually what I think you should

00:49:17.280 --> 00:49:19.280
take away from it. Yes, here's all the

00:49:19.280 --> 00:49:21.280
receipts. I have the plots. I have the methods.

00:49:21.280 --> 00:49:23.280
I have all that stuff, but I'm trying

00:49:23.280 --> 00:49:25.280
to convince you that this actually

00:49:25.280 --> 00:49:27.280
means this. I'm trying to convince

00:49:27.500 --> 00:49:29.500
you that we found this and it's important or

00:49:29.500 --> 00:49:31.500
we actually did all this

00:49:31.500 --> 00:49:33.500
work and we need to stop doing

00:49:33.500 --> 00:49:35.500
this because it's not

00:49:35.500 --> 00:49:37.500
working or our

00:49:37.500 --> 00:49:39.500
hypothesis was wrong or something like that.

00:49:39.500 --> 00:49:41.500
Maybe my biggest communication tip

00:49:41.500 --> 00:49:43.500
would be have a lot of

00:49:43.500 --> 00:49:45.500
TLDRs like executive summary

00:49:45.500 --> 00:49:47.500
like this is the number one thing

00:49:47.500 --> 00:49:49.500
you should take away from what I'm telling you

00:49:49.500 --> 00:49:51.500
and then here's a ton of backup. If you

00:49:51.500 --> 00:49:53.500
want to go through and see the nitty gritty detail, if you

00:49:53.500 --> 00:49:55.500
want to see my code, if you want to see everything, it's

00:49:55.719 --> 00:49:57.719
there, but the number one thing is this is

00:49:57.719 --> 00:49:59.719
what I want you to, I'm trying

00:49:59.719 --> 00:50:01.719
to persuade you of this point.

00:50:03.719 --> 00:50:05.719
I love that. I was just writing

00:50:05.719 --> 00:50:07.719
that time stamp down to remember

00:50:07.719 --> 00:50:09.719
to go back to that.

00:50:09.719 --> 00:50:11.719
Brittany, on that topic, I see you

00:50:11.719 --> 00:50:13.719
just put a great comment into the chat

00:50:13.719 --> 00:50:15.719
too if you'd want to expand

00:50:15.719 --> 00:50:17.719
on that.

00:50:17.719 --> 00:50:19.719
Yeah, I think

00:50:19.719 --> 00:50:21.719
I tend to mentor

00:50:21.719 --> 00:50:23.719
a lot of analysts, more junior

00:50:23.939 --> 00:50:25.939
analysts at my company and one thing

00:50:25.939 --> 00:50:27.939
that I notice is you can tell that someone's

00:50:27.939 --> 00:50:29.939
growing in their career when they go from

00:50:29.939 --> 00:50:31.939
this is the road I took

00:50:31.939 --> 00:50:33.939
and then finally telling you

00:50:33.939 --> 00:50:35.939
why you should care about all the stuff

00:50:35.939 --> 00:50:37.939
I just told you before versus

00:50:37.939 --> 00:50:39.939
lead with the headline and start with what people

00:50:39.939 --> 00:50:41.939
care about and sometimes the

00:50:41.939 --> 00:50:43.939
people that you're working with will want to know how

00:50:43.939 --> 00:50:45.939
you got there and sometimes they won't.

00:50:45.939 --> 00:50:47.939
Then you just give yourself and them a whole

00:50:47.939 --> 00:50:49.939
lot of headache by doing it that way.

00:50:49.939 --> 00:50:51.939
Totally and I think that people

00:50:52.159 --> 00:50:54.159
I have to say I make this mistake

00:50:54.159 --> 00:50:56.159
myself all the time. I'll talk

00:50:56.159 --> 00:50:58.159
to somebody and I'll think, whoa, I messed that up.

00:50:58.159 --> 00:51:00.159
I should have been way more short.

00:51:00.159 --> 00:51:02.159
I didn't need all that detail or whatever.

00:51:02.159 --> 00:51:04.159
I think it is something that no matter

00:51:04.159 --> 00:51:06.159
if it's your first day or your

00:51:06.159 --> 00:51:08.159
10,000th

00:51:08.159 --> 00:51:10.159
day, we all use

00:51:10.159 --> 00:51:12.159
reminders on that actually because

00:51:12.159 --> 00:51:14.159
sometimes we default to

00:51:14.159 --> 00:51:16.159
I'm just going to show you what I did versus why you

00:51:16.159 --> 00:51:18.159
should care.

00:51:18.379 --> 00:51:20.379
I love this

00:51:20.379 --> 00:51:22.379
discussion. If other people have tips

00:51:22.379 --> 00:51:24.379
or anything you want to add as

00:51:24.379 --> 00:51:26.379
well, this is really

00:51:26.379 --> 00:51:28.379
helpful for me too. I feel

00:51:28.379 --> 00:51:30.379
like sometimes I try to fit way too much

00:51:30.379 --> 00:51:32.379
into those 30-minute meetings

00:51:32.379 --> 00:51:34.379
that you have.

00:51:34.379 --> 00:51:36.379
I think sometimes I go too far

00:51:36.379 --> 00:51:38.379
too. I've had a couple recently

00:51:38.379 --> 00:51:40.379
where

00:51:40.379 --> 00:51:42.379
I assumed I was like, they're not going to want to see

00:51:42.379 --> 00:51:44.379
the data and then my

00:51:44.379 --> 00:51:46.379
coworkers are like, yes, they want to see the data

00:51:46.600 --> 00:51:48.600
and then I sent them the data and they

00:51:48.600 --> 00:51:50.600
came back and they actually went through everything.

00:51:50.600 --> 00:51:52.600
I was like, oh, okay. I shouldn't

00:51:52.600 --> 00:51:54.600
assume that if somebody

00:51:54.600 --> 00:51:56.600
is an executive, they want only two sentences.

00:51:56.600 --> 00:51:58.600
They might actually want to see more.

00:52:02.600 --> 00:52:04.600
Awesome.

00:52:04.600 --> 00:52:06.600
One other question was

00:52:06.600 --> 00:52:08.600
I imagine this is not an issue at

00:52:08.600 --> 00:52:10.600
a startup. However,

00:52:10.600 --> 00:52:12.600
in past workplaces,

00:52:12.600 --> 00:52:14.600
have you had any challenges with

00:52:14.820 --> 00:52:16.820
colleagues misperceiving your

00:52:16.820 --> 00:52:18.820
inquisitiveness?

00:52:20.820 --> 00:52:22.820
No.

00:52:22.820 --> 00:52:24.820
I think that's interesting though.

00:52:26.820 --> 00:52:28.820
I'm generally

00:52:28.820 --> 00:52:30.820
a very curious person. I have a lot of

00:52:30.820 --> 00:52:32.820
interests.

00:52:32.820 --> 00:52:34.820
I think

00:52:34.820 --> 00:52:36.820
you have to know when there's a time and a place

00:52:36.820 --> 00:52:38.820
for being like talking a lot

00:52:38.820 --> 00:52:40.820
versus not talking.

00:52:40.820 --> 00:52:42.820
That's a great place to

00:52:43.040 --> 00:52:45.040
ask your colleagues and stuff for feedback.

00:52:47.040 --> 00:52:49.040
To be like, okay,

00:52:49.040 --> 00:52:51.040
is it just me or was I the only one talking

00:52:51.040 --> 00:52:53.040
in that meeting?

00:52:53.040 --> 00:52:55.040
No, I can't think of a time

00:52:55.040 --> 00:52:57.040
to be honest

00:52:57.040 --> 00:52:59.040
where it was

00:52:59.040 --> 00:53:01.040
necessarily misinterpreted.

00:53:01.040 --> 00:53:03.040
I think I've been very fortunate

00:53:03.040 --> 00:53:05.040
to work in research settings

00:53:05.040 --> 00:53:07.040
where

00:53:07.040 --> 00:53:09.040
curiosity is rewarded

00:53:09.040 --> 00:53:11.040
and people are also

00:53:11.260 --> 00:53:13.260
very

00:53:13.260 --> 00:53:15.260
accepting

00:53:15.260 --> 00:53:17.260
of you asking

00:53:17.260 --> 00:53:19.260
questions.

00:53:19.260 --> 00:53:21.260
I'm not afraid

00:53:21.260 --> 00:53:23.260
if I don't know something, I'll ask.

00:53:23.260 --> 00:53:25.260
I think that's always been

00:53:25.260 --> 00:53:27.260
I actually respect

00:53:27.260 --> 00:53:29.260
that a lot in people. Maybe back to

00:53:29.260 --> 00:53:31.260
the leadership question,

00:53:31.260 --> 00:53:33.260
people who know what they know

00:53:33.260 --> 00:53:35.260
are comfortable with what they don't know.

00:53:35.260 --> 00:53:37.260
If

00:53:37.260 --> 00:53:39.260
you don't know something in a meeting,

00:53:39.479 --> 00:53:41.479
I'm happy to ask

00:53:41.479 --> 00:53:43.479
about it, even if it's something that's really basic

00:53:43.479 --> 00:53:45.479
for somebody else. If I don't know it,

00:53:45.479 --> 00:53:47.479
that's fine. I really respect

00:53:47.479 --> 00:53:49.479
that in leaders that I've seen who will say

00:53:49.479 --> 00:53:51.479
like, you know what, I have no idea what

00:53:51.479 --> 00:53:53.479
precision means, so you're going to

00:53:53.479 --> 00:53:55.479
have to explain it to me.

00:53:57.479 --> 00:53:59.479
That's a great point. I know

00:53:59.479 --> 00:54:01.479
an hour is going by

00:54:01.479 --> 00:54:03.479
very quickly, but I know

00:54:03.479 --> 00:54:05.479
when we first

00:54:05.479 --> 00:54:07.479
met, actually, I think it was on the OurLadies

00:54:07.699 --> 00:54:09.699
Slack discussion, we

00:54:09.699 --> 00:54:11.699
talked a little bit about a role

00:54:11.699 --> 00:54:13.699
that you were hiring for and your

00:54:13.699 --> 00:54:15.699
thoughts around hiring. I just was

00:54:15.699 --> 00:54:17.699
curious, are you still hiring

00:54:17.699 --> 00:54:19.699
now? I am. I think that

00:54:19.699 --> 00:54:21.699
is also another difference between a big company

00:54:21.699 --> 00:54:23.699
and a small company is that

00:54:23.699 --> 00:54:25.699
at a big company, you kind of

00:54:25.699 --> 00:54:27.699
have a lot of

00:54:27.699 --> 00:54:29.699
baggage, maybe, that people know

00:54:29.699 --> 00:54:31.699
about the company. That can be a huge incentive

00:54:31.699 --> 00:54:33.699
because they're like, oh, great, look at this

00:54:33.699 --> 00:54:35.699
great company. It's a big company. I want to work

00:54:35.919 --> 00:54:37.919
there. You get a lot of

00:54:37.919 --> 00:54:39.919
the work done for you

00:54:39.919 --> 00:54:41.919
of explaining the company.

00:54:41.919 --> 00:54:43.919
When I've been hiring for my new job,

00:54:43.919 --> 00:54:45.919
at least until recently,

00:54:45.919 --> 00:54:47.919
we didn't have a website.

00:54:47.919 --> 00:54:49.919
We had three employees.

00:54:49.919 --> 00:54:51.919
I had to work a lot

00:54:51.919 --> 00:54:53.919
within my network to be like, okay, let me

00:54:53.919 --> 00:54:55.919
explain to you. Please just give me

00:54:55.919 --> 00:54:57.919
an opening, and then now

00:54:57.919 --> 00:54:59.919
since you know nothing about the company,

00:54:59.919 --> 00:55:01.919
I'm going to have to explain it to you

00:55:01.919 --> 00:55:03.919
a lot more than I had to in the past

00:55:04.139 --> 00:55:06.139
when it was like, have you heard of Johnson

00:55:06.139 --> 00:55:08.139
and Johnson?

00:55:08.139 --> 00:55:10.139
People kind of know it, and they're not as

00:55:10.139 --> 00:55:12.139
there's less work there

00:55:12.139 --> 00:55:14.139
to do that, but I would actually love, I don't know

00:55:14.139 --> 00:55:16.139
if we have time yet for people to talk about if they've

00:55:16.139 --> 00:55:18.139
had any particularly positive or negative

00:55:18.139 --> 00:55:20.139
remote hiring experiences

00:55:20.139 --> 00:55:22.139
because that's been something I've been kind of

00:55:22.139 --> 00:55:24.139
experimenting with is how

00:55:24.139 --> 00:55:26.139
do I make an interview a good

00:55:26.139 --> 00:55:28.139
experience for a candidate because at the end of

00:55:28.139 --> 00:55:30.139
the day, I'm trying to sell them. I'm like, come work with

00:55:30.139 --> 00:55:32.139
us. I want you to be excited about

00:55:32.360 --> 00:55:34.360
coming to this job.

00:55:34.360 --> 00:55:36.360
I don't want the interview to be too long,

00:55:36.360 --> 00:55:38.360
but I also don't want it to be too short because

00:55:38.360 --> 00:55:40.360
then they're not going to know enough about the job

00:55:40.360 --> 00:55:42.360
to come and do it. I would love

00:55:42.360 --> 00:55:44.360
to hear if people have tips or

00:55:44.360 --> 00:55:46.360
particularly good

00:55:46.360 --> 00:55:48.360
or even a particular nightmare. I would love

00:55:48.360 --> 00:55:50.360
to hear a hiring nightmare situation

00:55:50.360 --> 00:55:52.360
so that I can never do that.

00:55:52.360 --> 00:55:54.360
Yeah, because

00:55:54.360 --> 00:55:56.360
hiring remote is definitely

00:55:58.360 --> 00:56:00.360
it creates new challenges.

00:56:02.360 --> 00:56:04.360
Javier, yes.

00:56:06.360 --> 00:56:08.360
Yeah, just in

00:56:08.360 --> 00:56:10.360
terms of the nightmare situation,

00:56:12.360 --> 00:56:14.360
this was years ago, about 10 years ago,

00:56:14.360 --> 00:56:16.360
but we hired someone

00:56:16.360 --> 00:56:18.360
this was before I got

00:56:18.360 --> 00:56:20.360
into the way I'm using R today

00:56:20.360 --> 00:56:22.360
and Python and whatnot, but

00:56:22.360 --> 00:56:24.360
we were giving

00:56:24.360 --> 00:56:26.360
Excel technical interviews

00:56:26.360 --> 00:56:28.360
and we were telling all the candidates in advance

00:56:28.360 --> 00:56:30.360
we're going to be doing Excel technical interviews

00:56:30.580 --> 00:56:32.580
and this one individual

00:56:32.580 --> 00:56:34.580
blew it out of the park.

00:56:35.580 --> 00:56:37.580
It turns out that

00:56:37.580 --> 00:56:39.580
they must have

00:56:39.580 --> 00:56:41.580
