00:56:41.580 --> 00:56:43.580
the basics that we were looking

00:56:43.580 --> 00:56:45.580
for.

00:56:45.580 --> 00:56:47.580
Since then,

00:56:47.580 --> 00:56:49.580
I have had way more success

00:56:49.580 --> 00:56:51.580
not giving that kind of technical interview

00:56:51.580 --> 00:56:53.580
and literally the technical interview

00:56:53.580 --> 00:56:55.580
is more of a discussion. I would

00:56:55.580 --> 00:56:57.580
much rather prefer hiring someone

00:56:57.580 --> 00:56:59.580
if I asked them like, hey, you know how

00:56:59.800 --> 00:57:01.800
to develop shiny apps. I'd much

00:57:01.800 --> 00:57:03.800
rather someone tell me I've never developed

00:57:03.800 --> 00:57:05.800
a shiny app in my life,

00:57:05.800 --> 00:57:07.800
but I use R Markdown

00:57:07.800 --> 00:57:09.800
every day or

00:57:09.800 --> 00:57:11.800
that tells me a lot

00:57:11.800 --> 00:57:13.800
about their ability to actually jump

00:57:13.800 --> 00:57:15.800
in and learn something new and

00:57:15.800 --> 00:57:17.800
just their transparency. So I

00:57:17.800 --> 00:57:19.800
feel like the types of technical interviews

00:57:19.800 --> 00:57:21.800
I've had a lot of success

00:57:21.800 --> 00:57:23.800
with the last few years has been more

00:57:23.800 --> 00:57:25.800
like almost more

00:57:25.800 --> 00:57:27.800
like a discussion technical interview

00:57:28.020 --> 00:57:30.020
where I'm not even asking them to whiteboard

00:57:30.020 --> 00:57:32.020
anything or it's just talking.

00:57:32.020 --> 00:57:34.020
Yeah.

00:57:34.020 --> 00:57:36.020
No, I love that and that's what I'm trying

00:57:36.020 --> 00:57:38.020
to get at. If you

00:57:38.020 --> 00:57:40.020
have any good questions that you ask in those

00:57:40.020 --> 00:57:42.020
technical interview discussions or

00:57:42.020 --> 00:57:44.020
something, I would love to hear them

00:57:44.020 --> 00:57:46.020
because that's what I'm

00:57:46.020 --> 00:57:48.020
working on. I have this evolving

00:57:48.020 --> 00:57:50.020
list of interview questions

00:57:50.020 --> 00:57:52.020
and how we ask them

00:57:52.020 --> 00:57:54.020
to try to get at some of these things

00:57:54.020 --> 00:57:56.020
because in some ways I'm much more interested

00:57:56.239 --> 00:57:58.239
in the process, right?

00:57:58.239 --> 00:58:00.239
How do people approach

00:58:00.239 --> 00:58:02.239
a problem and solve challenges

00:58:02.239 --> 00:58:04.239
that they encounter versus

00:58:04.239 --> 00:58:06.239
the specific project

00:58:06.239 --> 00:58:08.239
they worked on? Because they're not

00:58:08.239 --> 00:58:10.239
going to work on that project ever again with me.

00:58:10.239 --> 00:58:12.239
It's going to be a new project, so they're

00:58:12.239 --> 00:58:14.239
going to have to learn something anyway.

00:58:14.239 --> 00:58:16.239
For sure.

00:58:16.239 --> 00:58:18.239
I've had like the last few

00:58:18.239 --> 00:58:20.239
roles I've placed have been

00:58:20.239 --> 00:58:22.239
exclusively from R

00:58:22.239 --> 00:58:24.239
related things, whether

00:58:24.459 --> 00:58:26.459
it's meetups or R hackathons

00:58:26.459 --> 00:58:28.459
or it's people I've met to the

00:58:28.459 --> 00:58:30.459
point where I'm starting to feel like I need

00:58:30.459 --> 00:58:32.459
to make more of an effort to get into

00:58:32.459 --> 00:58:34.459
a Python related hackathon or a Python

00:58:34.459 --> 00:58:36.459
conference or something

00:58:36.459 --> 00:58:38.459
where I might be over-indexing

00:58:38.459 --> 00:58:40.459
on R folks.

00:58:40.459 --> 00:58:42.459
But seeing

00:58:42.459 --> 00:58:44.459
these people at hackathons and the way

00:58:44.459 --> 00:58:46.459
they just problem solve

00:58:46.459 --> 00:58:48.459
in

00:58:48.459 --> 00:58:50.459
a day or four hours of

00:58:50.459 --> 00:58:52.459
seeing how someone thinks, you really

00:58:52.679 --> 00:58:54.679
get a lot of insight about these individuals.

00:58:56.679 --> 00:58:58.679
I don't know. Just some tips that have worked for me.

00:58:58.679 --> 00:59:00.679
That's awesome.

00:59:00.679 --> 00:59:02.679
Thank you. Brittany, I see you have your

00:59:02.679 --> 00:59:04.679
hand raised too. Do you want to jump in?

00:59:06.679 --> 00:59:08.679
Yeah, my company actually does.

00:59:08.679 --> 00:59:10.679
We do do a technical interview

00:59:10.679 --> 00:59:12.679
and we give candidates a

00:59:12.679 --> 00:59:14.679
data set while

00:59:14.679 --> 00:59:16.679
they're sort of on-site, whether that's them actually

00:59:16.679 --> 00:59:18.679
being on-site or just being in

00:59:18.679 --> 00:59:20.679
a Teams meeting. And then we give

00:59:20.899 --> 00:59:22.899
them maybe like an hour, hour and a half

00:59:22.899 --> 00:59:24.899
to actually just see what sorts of insights

00:59:24.899 --> 00:59:26.899
you find with a few very

00:59:26.899 --> 00:59:28.899
specifically directed questions.

00:59:28.899 --> 00:59:30.899
And what we're often looking

00:59:30.899 --> 00:59:32.899
for is not someone to have perfect

00:59:32.899 --> 00:59:34.899
answers to those questions. Kind of like

00:59:34.899 --> 00:59:36.899
what you said. It's really about understanding how

00:59:36.899 --> 00:59:38.899
did you look at the data set? What

00:59:38.899 --> 00:59:40.899
other information did you want?

00:59:40.899 --> 00:59:42.899
What do you wish you had more time

00:59:42.899 --> 00:59:44.899
to do? So you really get to

00:59:44.899 --> 00:59:46.899
see, like Javier said, how people are thinking,

00:59:46.899 --> 00:59:48.899
how they work through something.

00:59:49.120 --> 00:59:51.120
Especially if they don't have

00:59:51.120 --> 00:59:53.120
